        <h2>Police: The First Point of Failure</h2>
        <p>Arizona's law enforcement agencies operate with minimal transparency and maximal militarization. Phoenix Police Department leads the nation in officer-involved shootings, while smaller departments often have no civilian review boards. Our <strong>Criminal Legal System Reform</strong> program documented how "pretextual stops" disproportionately target Black and Latino drivers on Interstate 10 and Loop 202. These stops generate thousands of felony arrests that begin with minor violations.</p>
        <p>The problems extend to policing inside prisons. ADCRR's internal investigations classify 98% of use-of-force incidents as "justified" without external review. Our <strong>Independent Prison Oversight</strong> program exposed how officers who assault incarcerated people rarely face discipline, often receiving promotions instead. This culture of unaccountability begins with street policing and hardens inside prison walls.</p>
        <p>Police power structures also include AZPOST, which decertifies fewer than 1% of officers despite thousands of misconduct complaints. We've testified annually to expand AZPOST's authority and require public disclosure of officer misconduct files, facing fierce opposition from police unions at every turn.</p>
