        <h2>Pre-Trial & Prosecution: The Revolving Door of Injustice</h2>
        <p>Arizona's pre-trial system criminalizes poverty. County attorneys routinely request cash bail amounts 50% higher than national averages, leaving low-income people—disproportionately Black and Indigenous—jailed for weeks awaiting trial. Our <strong>Drug Policy & Overdose Prevention</strong> program documented cases of individuals detained for simple possession unable to afford $500 bail, losing jobs, housing, and custody while presumed innocent. We campaign to end cash bail for non-violent offenses.</p>
        <p>Prosecutors wield extraordinary power with zero accountability. County attorneys set policy through charging decisions that never face public review. Arizona's superior court system concentrates power in elected prosecutors who face voters only every four years. Our legislative advocacy focuses on requiring prosecutorial data transparency—tracking plea deal rates, charging disparities by race—while our <strong>Core Civics & Advocacy Training</strong> prepares community members to serve on prosecutorial review commissions.</p>
